Losing Supersymmetry 

Once again, we could examine how the above argument fares in the 
absence of supersymmetry. The conjecture is that if we start from 
the three-dimensional purely bosonic Lagrangian lag , then 
the relative dynamics of 
domain walls are described by the sine-Liouville theory with 
LagrangianL  =1 k-2 (y)^2+1 k ()^2
-^2e^-y where  is related to the separation of the walls. There are two key differences 
between this Lagrangian and the super-Liouville theory. The first is that 
shifts of  are no longer a symmetry in the bosonic case. The second is
that  the model is unstable for , mimicking the fact that the coset 
construction of the black hole only makes sense for .

Can we reproduce sinelv  from domain wall dynamics? Unfortunately, 
and in contrast to Section 2, supersymmetry played a vital role in 
determining the domain wall dynamics in this Section. 
Without the strong holomorphic (in fact, hyperKahler) restrictions 
imposed by supersymmetry on the low-energy three-dimensional effective 
action intout , we have 
no control over the physics near 
the vacua . Nonetheless, it is interesting to note that at least the 
symmetries coincide with the sine-Liouville potential. To see this, recall 
that the existence of two periodic collective coordinates  and 
 in the supersymmetric case 
can be traced to the second term in second  which  
first appeared as a  coupling in 
intout . In the original variables of the  gauge field, this term 
takes the form 
_ F_ _which arises at one-loop from a triangle graph with fermions running in 
the loop (as is clear from the tell-tale presence of the -symbol). 
We see therefore that the three-dimensional fermions provide the delicate 
mechanism by which the relative internal degree of freedom  preserves its 
shift symmetry. If we remove the fermions in three dimensions, there is 
nothing to prevent the appearance of  in the bosonic potential.


Discussion 


 
wall4.eps 
Two domain walls in the D2-D6 system. In contrast to other 
